    lessons_learned: ["Concentration risk is existential: Serving a single industry/customer segment creates correlated failure modes. SVB's 'moat' (deep VC relationships) became a death spiral when the entire customer base faced the same macro headwinds simultaneously. Modern founders must build diversified customer bases or accept that concentration = fragility.","Asset-liability mismatch kills in rising rate environments: Borrowing short (deposits withdrawable anytime) and lending long (10-year bonds) works until it doesn't. The lesson: duration risk must be hedged, especially when your deposit base is flighty venture-backed companies burning cash. Modern treasury management requires dynamic hedging, not set-and-forget bond portfolios.","Social media accelerates bank runs by 100x: The first Twitter-driven bank run moved $42B in 24 hours—faster than any historical precedent. In the age of instant communication and digital banking, confidence is binary and collapse is instantaneous. Modern financial infrastructure must be designed for panic-speed withdrawals and real-time transparency to prevent information cascades.","Regulatory arbitrage is a time bomb: SVB lobbied to avoid enhanced oversight, then grew into systemic importance without implementing required controls. The 8-month vacancy in the Chief Risk Officer role during a historic rate hiking cycle was negligent. Lesson: regulatory compliance isn't overhead—it's insurance against catastrophic failure. Cutting corners on risk management to boost short-term profitability is suicidal.","Mark-to-market matters even if you pretend it doesn't: SVB's $91B 'held-to-maturity' portfolio hid $15B in unrealized losses until forced selling exposed them. Accounting games don't change economic reality. Modern founders must understand that 'paper losses' become real losses when liquidity demands force asset sales. Transparency and real-time risk reporting prevent surprises.","Network effects cut both ways: SVB's tight integration with the VC ecosystem (YC, a16z, Founders Fund) was a growth engine and a kill switch. When influential VCs told portfolio companies to withdraw, the network effect reversed into a death spiral. Modern platforms must design for resilience against coordinated exits—diversification, circuit breakers, and multi-homing incentives.","Liquidity is survival: SVB had $209B in assets but couldn't convert them to cash fast enough to meet $42B in withdrawal requests. The lesson: balance sheet size means nothing if assets are illiquid. Modern financial infrastructure must maintain high-quality liquid assets (HQLA) proportional to flighty deposits, even if it reduces yield.","Regulatory capture and political lobbying create moral hazard: SVB's CEO was on the San Francisco Fed board while lobbying to reduce oversight. This conflict of interest prevented early intervention. Modern founders should be wary of industries where regulatory capture allows dangerous practices to persist until catastrophic failure."],
