    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Capital-intensive marketplaces must achieve unit-level profitability in ONE market before geographic expansion. Getir's simultaneous 9-country launch was a $1B+ mistake—each market required 18-24 months to mature, fragmenting focus and preventing iterative learning. Modern founders should follow DoorDash's playbook: dominate a single dense city, prove the model works, then expand methodically with a refined playbook.","Quick commerce is operationally intensive, not tech-differentiated. Getir's competitive moat was supposed to be speed, but competitors replicated 10-15 minute delivery within months. The real barriers are operational excellence (dark store utilization, supplier relationships, courier retention) and capital efficiency. AI can optimize routing and forecasting, but cannot solve the fundamental challenge of high fixed costs and low AOV.","Subsidized demand is not real demand. Getir's 50% discount promotions drove order volume but trained customers to never pay full price. When subsidies were reduced in 2023 to stem losses, order frequency dropped 60-70% in international markets. Sustainable businesses must validate willingness-to-pay early, even if it slows initial growth. Retention cohorts at full price are the only metric that matters.","Marketplace density is non-negotiable for delivery economics. Getir needed 80+ orders per dark store per day to breakeven, achievable only in ultra-dense areas (>15,000 people per km²). Expanding to sprawling US suburbs where density was 3,000-5,000 people per km² guaranteed failure. Modern founders must ruthlessly define their geographic TAM based on density thresholds and resist the temptation to expand into marginal markets.","Vertical integration beats horizontal aggregation in logistics. Gopuff survived by owning inventory and controlling the full stack, while Getir's asset-light approach (leasing dark stores, gig couriers) provided flexibility but no cost advantages. In capital-intensive businesses, owning critical assets (real estate, fleet, inventory) provides leverage during downturns and better unit economics at scale.","Acqui-hiring competitors during a downturn is a distraction, not a solution. The Gorillas acquisition consumed $1.2B and 6+ months of management focus integrating overlapping operations, when Getir should have been laser-focused on achieving profitability. Consolidation only works if it immediately improves unit economics or eliminates irrational competition—neither happened here.","Market timing risk is existential for capital-intensive models. Getir raised $1.8B at a $12B valuation in 2021 when capital was free, then faced a 2022-2023 environment where follow-on funding evaporated. Businesses requiring multiple funding rounds to reach profitability must stress-test their model against 24+ months of zero capital availability. The prudent strategy is to raise enough in good times to reach breakeven, not to fund maximum growth."],
