    description: "China's ESPN with $1.7B to buy every major sports league—NBA, Premier League, F1—and capture 300M emerging middle-class fans.",
    industry: "Communication Services",
    cause_of_death: "Burned $1.5B on sports rights but only got 4M paying subscribers when they needed 50M—turns out Chinese fans expect sports for free.",
    death_category: "run_out_of_cash",
    money_raised: 1700000000,
    money_burned: 1700000000,
    founded_year: 2014,
    died_year: 2018,
    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Premium content rights are a trap for startups: LeSports spent 75% of funding on content acquisition, creating fixed costs that scaled faster than revenue. Modern founders should focus on user-generated content, creator partnerships (revenue share vs. upfront fees), or niche sports with lower rights costs. The 'YouTube model' (platform for creators) beats the 'Netflix model' (licensed content) for capital-constrained startups.","Unit economics must work at small scale: LeSports needed 50M subscribers to break even—an impossible target requiring $500M+ in marketing spend. A viable rebuild should be profitable at 100K users ($500K-1M ARR) by targeting high-ARPU niches (betting integration, B2B sports analytics, premium coaching content) rather than mass-market subscriptions.","Ecosystem strategies are execution traps: LeEco's vision of hardware-software-content integration sounded compelling but created operational complexity, capital requirements, and coordination failures that killed all business units simultaneously. Focus on one wedge product with clear monetization before expanding.","Piracy and free alternatives define your pricing ceiling: In markets with weak IP enforcement or strong free incumbents (CCTV in China, YouTube globally), subscription models must provide 10x value over free options. LeSports offered marginal convenience over pirated streams. Modern rebuilds need exclusive experiences (live betting, AI analysis, community features) that can't be pirated.","Network effects are the only moat in content platforms: LeSports had zero network effects—my watching didn't improve your experience. Contrast with Strava (social fitness), Discord (community), or Sorare (fantasy/trading). A modern sports platform must be social-first, with leaderboards, predictions, fan tokens, or creator communities that make the platform more valuable as users join.","AI can replace expensive human content production: LeSports spent $50M+ annually on original shows, commentary, and analysis. Today, GPT-4/Claude can generate real-time commentary in 50+ languages, create highlight reels via computer vision (Twelve Labs, Mux), and produce personalized content feeds. This reduces content costs by 80-90% while improving personalization.","Regulatory risk in China requires diversification: LeSports was vulnerable to sudden policy changes (sports broadcasting regulations, content censorship, foreign content restrictions). The 2018 crackdown on entertainment/sports content accelerated their demise. Modern startups in regulated markets need geographic diversification or regulatory arbitrage strategies (offshore entities, decentralized protocols).","Betting integration is the killer monetization for sports: LeSports missed the opportunity to integrate sports betting (illegal in China but legal in 100+ countries), which generates $50-200 ARPU vs. $3-5 for subscriptions. A modern rebuild in betting-legal markets (US, Europe, India) could achieve 20-40x higher revenue per user with the same content costs."],
