    died_year: 2011,
    country: "USA",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Capital-intensive hardware businesses cannot survive on technology differentiation alone when competing in commodity markets. Solyndra's panels were genuinely innovative, but innovation is worthless if your cost structure is 2x higher than competitors. The lesson: if you're building hardware, your primary competitive advantage must be cost, not features. Elegant engineering that costs more to produce is a liability, not an asset.","Betting your business model on external price assumptions (commodity costs, regulatory environments) is existential risk. Solyndra assumed silicon would stay expensive. When it didn't, they had no Plan B because their entire factory was specialized. The lesson: build optionality into your infrastructure, or ensure your unit economics work even in worst-case commodity price scenarios. Stress-test your model against a 10x price movement in key inputs.","Government subsidies and loan guarantees can be a trap that accelerates your death rather than enabling success. The $535M DOE loan allowed Solyndra to scale manufacturing before proving they could compete at market prices. This created enormous fixed costs and political scrutiny that made pivoting impossible. The lesson: use non-dilutive capital to prove product-market fit and unit economics, not to scale unproven business models. Government money often comes with strings that limit strategic flexibility when you need it most.","In hardware, the manufacturing process IS the product. Solyndra's cylindrical design required custom equipment that couldn't be repurposed. When the product failed, the entire capital investment was worthless. The lesson: design products that can be manufactured with flexible, general-purpose equipment, or ensure your manufacturing innovation provides a sustainable cost advantage, not just a feature advantage.","Market timing in hardware is binary. Software companies can iterate cheaply, but hardware companies must commit massive capital to a specific bet. Solyndra committed to CIGS technology just as silicon was about to become radically cheaper. The lesson: in capital-intensive businesses, be paranoid about macroeconomic trends that could obsolete your technology. Have kill switches and pivot plans before you pour concrete."],
