    id: "2109",
    name: "Missfresh",
    description: "Amazon Fresh meets Chinese megacities—30-minute grocery delivery from micro-warehouses promising to eliminate shopping friction forever.",
    industry: "Consumer",
    cause_of_death: "Spent $1.5B believing density would fix unit economics, but each warehouse hit order ceilings while burning $50K+ monthly to serve $15 orders.",
    death_category: "unit_economics",
    money_raised: 1500000000,
    money_burned: 1500000000,
    founded_year: 2014,
    died_year: 2022,
    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Geographic density has a ceiling in physical retail models. Missfresh assumed infinite density gains, but each micro-fulfillment center has a hard radius limit (3km for 30-min delivery) and a maximum serviceable population. Opening more locations doesn't improve economics; it fragments your customer base across more fixed-cost assets. The lesson: in asset-heavy models, map out the maximum theoretical order volume per location based on population density and realistic market share before assuming scale solves profitability.","Subsidy-dependent customer acquisition creates a death spiral in low-margin businesses. Missfresh's CAC was $30-50, but LTV was only $80-120 because subsidized customers churned immediately when prices normalized. In grocery, where margins are 20-30% and AOV is $15-20, you need organic retention to survive. The business model must work at full price from day one, or you're just renting customers with investor capital.","Perishable inventory is a tax on working capital that compounds with scale. Missfresh held 3-5 days of inventory across hundreds of SKUs per warehouse, with 5-10% spoilage rates. At 500 warehouses, this meant tens of millions in trapped capital and waste. The lesson: in fresh food, inventory turns are everything. Successful models (Costco, Trader Joe's) limit SKUs dramatically and turn inventory in 24-48 hours. If your model requires broad selection of perishables, you need supplier consignment or just-in-time delivery, not speculative stocking.","Front warehouse real estate is a sunk cost with no exit value. Unlike traditional retail, these weren't customer-facing stores with brand value or alternative use cases. When Missfresh failed, they had 500+ leases on cold storage facilities in residential areas with no resale market. The lesson: capital-intensive infrastructure plays require either (a) asset-light models through partnerships, or (b) assets with alternative use cases or resale value. Purpose-built infrastructure for a single business model is a bet-the-company risk.","Competing on speed in a commodity market requires structural cost advantages, not just operational excellence. Missfresh was faster than traditional e-commerce but paid a 40% cost premium for that speed (distributed warehouses, smaller delivery batches, higher labor costs). Customers valued speed, but not enough to pay premium prices for commodity groceries. The lesson: operational differentiation (speed, convenience) only creates defensibility if you can deliver it at cost parity or if customers will pay enough premium to cover the cost delta. Otherwise, you're just a more expensive version of the same product."],
