    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Maturity mismatch kills: Never fund long-duration, illiquid assets (real estate, private equity) with short-term liabilities (retail deposits/trust products) unless you have massive liquidity buffers or government backstops. Modern fintech must match asset-liability duration or face bank runs.","Regulatory arbitrage is not a moat: Zhongzhi's entire model relied on exploiting gaps in China's financial regulations. When regulators closed those gaps (as they inevitably do), the business evaporated. Sustainable fintech builds within regulatory frameworks, not around them.","Opacity is a bug, not a feature: Investors tolerated Zhongzhi's lack of transparency during boom times, but demanded it during stress. Modern wealth management must be radically transparent (real-time reporting, clear fee structures, auditable holdings) to build trust.","China's property sector was a systemic risk: Any business overexposed to Chinese real estate post-2015 was playing Russian roulette. Diversification across asset classes and geographies is non-negotiable for financial products.","High yields signal high risk: Promising 10%+ returns in a low-rate environment is a red flag. Sustainable fintech focuses on risk-adjusted returns and educates users on the risk-return tradeoff rather than chasing yield.","Ponzi dynamics are fragile: Using new investor capital to pay existing investors works until it doesn't. Modern platforms must have genuine cash flow from operations or transparent investment returns, not circular financing.","Regulatory crackdowns are predictable: China's 2021-2023 financial reforms were telegraphed years in advance. Founders must anticipate regulatory tightening and build businesses that thrive under stricter rules, not collapse.","Trust is the ultimate currency in fintech: Once lost (via missed payments, opacity, or scandal), it's nearly impossible to rebuild. Modern fintech must prioritize user trust through transparency, security, and consistent performance over growth-at-all-costs."],
