    description: "Electric flying taxis promising to turn your 90-minute commute into a 15-minute flight for the 1% who could afford it",
    industry: "Industrials",
    cause_of_death: "Burned $1.5B building flying cars nobody could afford while waiting for batteries that don't exist and regulators who move at the speed of continental drift",
    death_category: "run_out_of_cash",
    money_raised: 1500000000,
    money_burned: 1500000000,
    founded_year: 2015,
    died_year: 2025,
    country: "USA",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Deep-tech hardware requires 3x the capital and 2x the timeline you project—Lilium's $1.5B and 10-year runway was insufficient for a novel aircraft design requiring dual-continent certification. Modern founders should assume $5B+ total capital for aerospace ventures and structure financing in tranches tied to technical milestones, not market hype.","Regulatory risk is an existential moat AND threat—certification timelines are unpredictable and non-negotiable. Lilium's unique ducted fan design added 2-3 years vs. proven rotor configurations. The loot: choose architectures with regulatory precedent, or budget $100M+ and 3+ years for novel approaches. Engage certification authorities in year one, not year three.","Two-sided marketplace problems in hardware are 10x harder than software—Lilium needed vertiports (infrastructure), aircraft (manufacturing), pilots (training), passengers (demand), and regulators (approval) to align simultaneously. Unlike Uber which leveraged existing cars/drivers, eVTOL requires building every layer from scratch. The lesson: avoid businesses requiring synchronized infrastructure buildout unless you have $10B+ and government partnership.","Battery energy density is the binding constraint for electric aviation—current lithium-ion technology at ~260 Wh/kg provides only 60-80 mile range with acceptable safety margins. Lilium's 100+ mile regional routes required batteries that won't exist until 2030+. Modern founders must design around today's physics, not tomorrow's breakthroughs. The loot: build for 50-mile urban routes with existing batteries, or wait for solid-state technology to mature.","SPAC-era capital was a trap, not a triumph—Lilium's ability to raise $1.5B created a false sense of validation and encouraged over-hiring (1000+ employees) and over-ambitious timelines. When public markets closed, the burn rate became fatal. The lesson: raise for milestones, not headcount. A $200M Series B with 150 engineers focused on certification would have outlasted a $1.5B SPAC with 1000 employees building manufacturing before proving the aircraft works.","Competitor selection matters—Joby (backed by Toyota, $2B+ raised) and Archer (United Airlines partnership) chose simpler rotor designs and focused on FAA certification first. Lilium's dual EASA/FAA strategy and novel propulsion doubled risk. The loot: in regulated industries, fast-follower strategies with proven technology often beat first-mover innovation. Let others absorb regulatory uncertainty.","Unit economics must work at scale, not in theory—Lilium's projected $3-6 per passenger-mile was only achievable at 10,000+ aircraft production volumes with $50M+ annual revenue per aircraft. At low volumes, costs were $15-20 per passenger-mile, making it a luxury product with <1% market penetration. Modern founders should model economics at 100 units, not 10,000. If it doesn't work at small scale, it won't get to large scale."],
    market_potential_score: 5,
