    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Marketplace unit economics must work at small scale before geographic expansion. Youxin's strategy of 'grow first, optimize later' in a low-margin business was fatal. Modern founders should achieve profitability in 1-2 cities before scaling, using cohort analysis to prove LTV > 3x CAC.","High-touch operations kill software economics. Any business requiring physical inspection, logistics, or reconditioning per transaction will have linear cost scaling. Use AI/computer vision to automate inspection (smartphone photos → damage detection) and gig workers instead of full-time staff to variabilize costs.","Low purchase frequency categories need high AOV or repeat cross-sell. Used cars are bought once every 5-7 years, making CAC recovery impossible on single transactions. Modern rebuilds should focus on subscription models (car subscription services), repeat services (maintenance, insurance), or B2B customers with higher frequency.","Competing on advertising spend in commoditized markets is a death spiral. Youxin and Guazi spent billions on brand marketing with no differentiation, creating a prisoner's dilemma. Modern playbook: build organic growth loops (referral programs, content SEO) and focus on a defensible niche (EVs, luxury, commercial vehicles) rather than mass market.","Physical infrastructure creates negative operating leverage. Youxin's inspection centers and storage lots were fixed costs that didn't decline with volume. Modern approach: asset-light models using partner networks (existing mechanics, dealerships) or mobile inspection units that come to the customer.","China's regulatory environment can be an asset, not just a risk. The 2022 national vehicle history database reduced the need for proprietary data moats. Modern founders should design around regulatory infrastructure rather than duplicating it, focusing on value-added services (AI pricing, financing, warranties).","B2B has better unit economics than C2C in fragmented markets. Youxin's pivot to dealer auctions (B2B) came too late. Dealers transact 50-100x more frequently than consumers, have lower CAC, and accept lower service levels. A modern rebuild should start B2B, then expand to C2C once the supply side is locked in.","SPAC exits don't solve fundamental business problems. Youxin's 2021 SPAC gave temporary capital but didn't fix unit economics. The public market pressure for growth accelerated burn. Modern founders should avoid growth-at-all-costs financing structures unless the business model is proven profitable at scale."],
