    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Capital intensity is a moat only if you can actually deploy the capital efficiently. LeSee raised over $1.2 billion but never built a functioning factory or supply chain. Modern founders should use contract manufacturers and asset-light models until product-market fit is proven. Foxconn, Magna, and others now offer turnkey EV production.","Ecosystem strategies are a trap for startups. Apple and Amazon can pull it off because they have infinite capital and decades of operational excellence. LeSee tried to build phones, TVs, content, and cars simultaneously, ensuring mediocrity in all. Focus on one wedge, dominate it, then expand.","Founder credibility is everything in capital-intensive industries. Jia's history of overpromising and financial irregularities should have been disqualifying, but investors were blinded by China's EV hype. Due diligence on founder execution track record is non-negotiable.","Autonomous driving timelines were wildly optimistic in 2014-2017. Even Tesla with vastly more resources has not achieved Level 4 autonomy. Promising vaporware technology to raise capital is fraud, not vision. Modern founders should partner with proven AV stacks like Mobileye or Waymo rather than building from scratch.","Vertical integration in hardware is a trap unless you have Tesla-level execution. LeSee tried to build batteries, motors, software, and content in-house, multiplying complexity and capital requirements. Modern approach: integrate best-in-class components and focus on software differentiation.","Regulatory compliance in automotive is a decade-long process. LeSee had no credible path to crash testing, safety certification, or emissions compliance. Modern founders must budget 3-5 years and $100+ million just for regulatory approval.","Unit economics matter even in moonshots. LeSee had no plan to achieve positive gross margins on vehicles while also subsidizing content. Modern rebuild must have clear path to 40+ percent gross margins through software or services.","Fleeing your home country to avoid debt obligations is not a viable exit strategy. Jia's escape to the US destroyed any remaining credibility and ensured LeSee's IP was liquidated at fire-sale prices. Founders must face failures and wind down responsibly."],
