    lessons_learned: ["Hardware businesses cannot be funded like software companies. Proterra raised over $1B but needed patient, manufacturing-appropriate capital (debt, strategic corporate investors, government loans) rather than VC/SPAC money expecting 10x returns. If your business requires $500M in capex before achieving positive unit economics, venture capital is the wrong tool. The lesson: match your capital structure to your business model's cash conversion cycle and margin profile, not to what's fashionable in fundraising markets.","Negative gross margins cannot be fixed with scale in commoditized manufacturing. Proterra assumed that producing 5,000 buses instead of 500 would drive margins from -5% to +20%. This ignored that their primary cost (battery cells) was a pass-through from suppliers, and assembly labor doesn't scale linearly. In hardware, if your unit economics are broken at 100 units, they're often still broken at 10,000 units unless you control the core technology or have pricing power. The lesson: achieve positive unit economics at small scale before scaling, or vertically integrate into the component with the highest margin potential.","Government customers create existential concentration risk without long-term contracts. Proterra's revenue was 80%+ from municipal transit agencies making one-time purchases through competitive RFPs. Unlike enterprise SaaS with multi-year contracts, each sale was a discrete transaction. When federal funding dried up or cities delayed budgets, revenue disappeared overnight with no recurring base. The lesson: if selling to government, either secure multi-year service contracts (maintenance, charging, energy management) or diversify into commercial customers with faster decision cycles and repeat purchase behavior.","Proprietary technology in commodity markets only works if it's 10x better or creates lock-in. Proterra's battery and charging systems were incrementally better than competitors but not dramatically so. Transit agencies increasingly demanded interoperability and standardization rather than proprietary solutions. Without network effects or switching costs, proprietary tech became a liability (higher costs, vendor lock-in concerns) rather than a moat. The lesson: in B2B hardware, open standards and interoperability often win over proprietary systems unless your technology creates undeniable, measurable superiority that justifies the lock-in risk.","SPACs are terrible vehicles for capital-intensive businesses with long payback periods. The SPAC merger gave Proterra $500M but came with quarterly earnings pressure, retail investor volatility, and a ticking clock on profitability expectations. Manufacturing businesses need 5-7 years of patient capital to reach scale. Public markets punished them for missing quarterly targets, tanking the stock and making follow-on capital impossible. The lesson: if your business has multi-year capital needs before profitability, stay private longer or pursue strategic acquisition rather than SPAC/IPO. Public markets are unforgiving to pre-profitable hardware companies."],
