    money_burned: 1100000000,
    founded_year: 1969,
    died_year: 2016,
    country: "USA",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Outcomes-based monetization is the only ethical model for education: Income Share Agreements (pay % of salary only after job placement above threshold) align incentives and force focus on actual skill development rather than enrollment volume. Lambda School proved this model, though execution matters—ISAs must have caps and forgiveness terms.","Regulatory arbitrage is not a moat: Building a business dependent on government subsidy programs (Title IV, VA benefits) without delivering genuine value creates existential risk. The 2010-2016 for-profit education crackdown (Corinthian Colleges, ITT, University of Phoenix) proved regulators will eventually close exploitative loopholes. Sustainable education businesses must survive without government funding.","Brand trust in education is binary and irreversible: Once accreditation is revoked or fraud is exposed, there is no recovery. ITT's brand became toxic—degrees became resume liabilities. Modern rebuilds must obsess over Net Promoter Score, graduate outcomes transparency, and third-party validation (employer partnerships, certification body endorsements).","Physical infrastructure is a liability in digital-native markets: ITT's 130 campuses were $2B+ in sunk costs that became worthless overnight. The future of vocational education is remote-first with optional in-person intensives. Cloud labs (AWS, Azure sandboxes), VR simulations (Unity-based training), and AI pair programming (Cursor, GitHub Copilot) replicate hands-on learning at 1/100th the cost.","Sales-driven growth in education creates adverse selection: High-pressure enrollment tactics attract the least prepared students (those who can be manipulated) rather than the most motivated. Product-led growth with rigorous admissions (coding challenges, prerequisite tests) filters for commitment and ability to benefit, improving completion rates and outcomes.","Accreditation is a double-edged sword: Traditional accreditation (ACICS in ITT's case) provides legitimacy but moves slowly and can be revoked. Modern alternatives—employer recognition (Google Career Certificates accepted by 150+ companies), competency-based credentials (Credly badges), and direct hiring pipelines (Multiverse, Revature)—bypass accreditation entirely and prove value through job placement.","The 90/10 rule (90% federal funding cap for for-profits) exists because 100% government-funded models have zero market discipline: If students/employers won't pay anything out-of-pocket, the product likely has no real value. Modern rebuilds should target 50%+ non-government revenue (employer sponsorships, corporate training contracts, international students) to prove market validation.","Default rates are the ultimate outcomes metric: ITT's 40%+ loan default rate was a flashing red signal ignored for years. Any education business should publish cohort-level default rates, employment rates at 6/12/24 months, and salary data. Transparency is the only path to trust post-ITT."],
