    founder_count: 2,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["SPAC funding is poison for hardware companies. The structure forces you to spend capital proving a thesis (production at scale) before you've solved the actual problem (unit economics and manufacturing quality). Software companies can iterate cheaply; hardware companies need patient capital that accepts 5-7 year timelines to profitability. Lordstown raised $675M from their SPAC but needed $2B+ to reach sustainable production. The mismatch killed them—they were forced to rush production to satisfy public market expectations, shipping defective vehicles that destroyed their reputation. Lesson: Hardware startups should raise from strategics, sovereign wealth funds, or family offices who understand decade-long horizons, not retail investors expecting Tesla-like returns.","Pre-orders without deposits are marketing theater, not demand validation. Lordstown claimed 100,000 pre-orders but required no money down and no binding commitments. When Hindenburg investigated, they found orders came from entities with no capital to actually purchase trucks. Real demand validation requires: (1) meaningful deposits ($1,000+ per unit), (2) diversified customer base (not one entity representing 80% of 'orders'), and (3) letters of intent with delivery timelines from creditworthy buyers. Fleet buyers are sophisticated—they'll sign non-binding LOIs to hedge their bets across multiple vendors. Lordstown's fraud wasn't just unethical; it misallocated capital toward production capacity they didn't need, rather than engineering the product to work.","Proprietary technology in hardware is a liability until you achieve scale. Hub motors were Lordstown's differentiation but became their execution anchor. Each hub motor was a custom assembly with no existing supply chain, requiring them to vertically integrate manufacturing for a component that represented 40% of vehicle cost. Compare to Rivian, which used a skateboard platform with conventional motors—they could source from Bosch, Continental, or other tier-1 suppliers with decades of quality control. Proprietary tech works when you have Tesla's capital to build the supply chain yourself. For startups, the winning move is: use commodity components to reach 10,000 units, then backward integrate once you have cash flow and negotiating leverage.","Manufacturing 'assets' are liabilities until you hit 60%+ capacity utilization. Lordstown bought a 6.2M sq ft plant designed for 400,000 vehicles/year when they needed to build 3,000 in year one. Fixed costs (utilities, security, maintenance, property taxes) ran $50M+ annually regardless of output. This is the 'factory trap'—politicians love ribbon cuttings, but empty factories burn cash. Tesla understood this: they started with the Fremont plant at 10% capacity and expanded incrementally. Lordstown should have contracted manufacturing with Magna Steyr or Foxconn from day one, paying $5,000/unit in manufacturing fees until they had proven demand. Instead, they spent $230M acquiring and retooling a plant that became an albatross.","The commercial fleet market demands service infrastructure before sales. Lordstown focused on vehicle engineering but ignored the service network required for fleet buyers. A municipal utility with 50 trucks needs same-day parts availability and certified technicians within 100 miles. Ford and GM have 3,000+ service centers; Lordstown had zero. Fleet buyers calculate total cost of ownership over 10 years—a $52,500 truck with no service network is more expensive than a $65,000 F-150 Lightning with dealer support. This is why Tesla struggled with commercial sales until they built out their service infrastructure. The lesson: for B2B hardware, distribution and service are 50% of the product. Lordstown should have partnered with an existing dealer network (Penske, Ryder) from day one, even at the cost of margin."],
    market_potential_score: 5,
