    cause_of_death: "Burned $100M/year on marketing while giving 70% of revenue to universities, then bought edX to compete with themselves.",
    death_category: "run_out_of_cash",
    money_raised: 1000000000,
    money_burned: 1000000000,
    founded_year: 2008,
    died_year: 2024,
    country: "USA",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Revenue-share models with suppliers (universities) are death traps in edtech. You're a margin-squeezed middleman with no pricing power. Own the content or own the customer relationship — never split both.","Expensive online degrees ($20K-60K) only work if employers pay (tuition reimbursement) or outcomes are guaranteed (ISAs). Direct-to-consumer learners won't pay more than $500 unless there's a clear ROI (promotion, job switch). 2U's $40K master's programs were luxury goods in a commodity market.","M&A in edtech is a graveyard. 2U, Chegg, Coursera all destroyed value with acquisitions. The integration costs (tech stack consolidation, brand confusion, cultural clashes) exceed synergies. Organic growth or acqui-hires only.","Human-intensive delivery (TAs, advisors, career coaches) doesn't scale. 2U had 4,000+ employees for $1B revenue ($250K revenue/employee vs. $1M+ for SaaS). AI tutors (GPT-4 fine-tuned on course content) can replace 80% of TA work at 1/100th the cost.","University partnerships are slow, political, and fragile. Sales cycles are 12-18 months, contracts have enrollment guarantees (downside risk), and universities can terminate or build in-house. Go direct to learners or sell to employers (Udemy Business model) for faster iteration.","Cohort-based programs create lumpy revenue and CAC spikes. 2U had to fill entire cohorts (30-50 students) every 6 months, leading to panic spending on ads. Asynchronous, self-paced learning (Coursera model) smooths revenue and reduces CAC by 50%+.","Debt-fueled growth in edtech is suicide. 2U borrowed $1B+ to fund marketing spend, betting on future cash flows. When growth slowed, the debt spiral killed them. Bootstrap or raise equity — never lever up a negative-margin business.","The pandemic online education boom was a mirage. 2U's revenue spiked 20% in 2020-2021 as universities scrambled online, but it was pull-forward demand. By 2022, enrollments cratered as students returned to campus and realized online degrees weren't worth the premium."],
    market_potential_score: 8,
    rebuild_difficulty: 2,
    tags: ["edtech"],
    created_at: "2026-02-01T21:33:19.568842+00:00",
