    money_burned: 1000000000,
    founded_year: 2015,
    died_year: 2024,
    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Platform businesses require platform economics: Koala operated a capital-heavy hybrid model (self-operated inventory + marketplace) that combined the worst of both worlds—high working capital needs without marketplace scalability. Modern founders should choose: pure marketplace (zero inventory risk) or vertical brand (own the product). Hybrid models only work at massive scale.","Regulatory arbitrage is not a moat: Koala's early growth exploited temporary tax advantages that were always going to close. Any business model dependent on regulatory loopholes has a built-in expiration date. Sustainable advantages must be operational (supply chain, brand, technology) not regulatory.","In China's internet economy, you're either Alibaba/Tencent or you're their exit strategy: NetEase learned that independent e-commerce platforms can't survive against BAT (Baidu, Alibaba, Tencent) ecosystem players who can subsidize indefinitely from other profit centers. The only winning move is to build something the giants can't easily replicate (deep vertical expertise, community, or technology) and sell at peak valuation.","Authentication and trust are table stakes, not differentiators: By 2019, every platform offered 'guaranteed authentic' products with blockchain tracking, third-party verification, and direct brand partnerships. What started as Koala's core value prop became an industry standard, eliminating their differentiation. Founders must identify which of their 'unique' features will be commoditized in 18-24 months.","Bonded warehouse infrastructure is a trap: Koala spent $300M+ building physical infrastructure that became stranded assets post-acquisition. In 2024, this infrastructure is available as a service from dozens of providers. Capital-intensive moats only work if you can achieve monopoly scale before competitors catch up—otherwise you've just built expensive assets that don't compound.","Customer acquisition cost trajectory predicts marketplace death: Koala's CAC increased 5x in 3 years while competitor subsidies made organic retention impossible. In marketplace businesses, once CAC exceeds lifetime value and you lack the capital to subsidize, you're in a death spiral. Modern founders must model CAC inflation scenarios and have a plan for when incumbents decide to compete on price.","Cross-border e-commerce is now a vertical game: The horizontal 'everything store' model is dead—Alibaba and Amazon won. Opportunities exist in hyper-vertical niches where deep supplier relationships, community trust, and specialized logistics create defensibility. Think 'the Koala for Japanese skincare' not 'the next Koala.'"],
    market_potential_score: 8,
