    cause_of_death: "Spent $960M building cold-chain infrastructure that became an albatross when hybrid competitors achieved better unit economics.",
    death_category: "unit_economics",
    money_raised: 960000000,
    money_burned: 960000000,
    founded_year: 2005,
    died_year: 2020,
    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Infrastructure-as-moat only works if you can achieve 3x better unit economics than asset-light competitors. Yiguo's cold-chain network cost $300M to build but was underutilized (40% capacity) in most markets. Modern approach: rent infrastructure until you prove demand density justifies ownership. Use 3PL partners for logistics until order volume in a single micro-market (5km radius) exceeds 500 orders/day.","In fresh food delivery, customer lifetime value is capped by frequency and basket size, both of which are culturally constrained. Chinese consumers preferred daily small purchases at wet markets (social experience, freshness verification) over weekly bulk orders. Yiguo's LTV never exceeded $180 despite 15 years of market education. Lesson: if your model requires changing deeply embedded cultural behaviors, you need a 10x better product, not 2x. Yiguo was 2x more convenient but 1.5x more expensive and offered less freshness certainty.","Horizontal fresh delivery is a negative-sum game in low-density markets. Yiguo's mistake was treating all cities equally. In tier-1 cities (Beijing, Shanghai), they achieved 200-300 orders per square kilometer; in tier-3 cities, it was 20-30. The latter never covered delivery costs ($4-7 per order). Correct strategy: dominate one neighborhood (5,000 households) with 40%+ penetration before expanding to the next. Density is everything—better to own 3 neighborhoods than have 1% share in 300 cities.","The business model must work at full price before you subsidize for growth. Yiguo subsidized 30-50% of order value for years, assuming scale would fix margins. It didn't—spoilage, delivery costs, and CAC remained constant percentages. They never tested whether customers would pay true cost. Modern discipline: achieve positive contribution margin in one micro-market at full price, then use subsidy strategically only for customer acquisition in proven geos.","In two-sided marketplaces with perishable inventory, supply-side leverage matters more than demand. Yiguo focused on consumer marketing but had weak relationships with farmers and wholesalers, leading to inconsistent quality and 35% spoilage rates. Competitors who controlled supply (Hema with direct farm contracts, Pinduoduo with cooperative aggregation) achieved 15-20% spoilage and better margins. Lesson: in fresh food, owning or tightly integrating supply is the only way to control quality and costs. Demand is easy to generate with subsidies; reliable supply at target margins is the actual constraint."],
