    id: "2563",
    name: "Plenty Unlimited",
    description: "Vertical farming using AI and robotics to grow pesticide-free produce with 99% less water and land than traditional agriculture.",
    industry: "Materials",
    cause_of_death: "Unit economics never worked: $1B couldn't overcome energy costs, construction expenses, and inability to compete with $2 lettuce.",
    death_category: "unit_economics",
    money_raised: 944000000,
    money_burned: 944000000,
    founded_year: 2014,
    died_year: 2025,
    country: "USA",
    founder_count: 2,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Unit economics must be proven at small scale before raising growth capital. Plenty raised $944M without ever demonstrating profitability at a single facility. Modern founders should build a single profitable micro-farm (even 1000 sq ft) and prove the full P&L before scaling. Use tools like Causal or Runway for rigorous financial modeling with sensitivity analysis on energy costs, yield rates, and pricing. If unit economics don't work at small scale, they won't magically improve at large scale—capital only amplifies the problem.","Beware of competing against free inputs from nature. Sunlight, rain, and land in agricultural regions are essentially free or very cheap. Any technology solution must overcome this massive subsidy. Vertical farming makes sense only in contexts where conventional agriculture is impossible: space stations, arctic research bases, or post-climate-collapse scenarios. For Earth-based applications, focus on high-value crops where quality premiums justify costs: saffron, rare medicinal herbs, or genetically modified organisms that require containment. Lettuce was the wrong wedge—it's a commodity with razor-thin margins.","Infrastructure businesses disguised as tech platforms are capital traps. Plenty's pitch deck probably showed software-like gross margins (80%+) by excluding facility CapEx and energy costs. In reality, they were a utilities and real estate business with 20-30% gross margins at best. Modern founders should be brutally honest about capital intensity. If your business requires $50M+ per location and has linear scaling, you're building a franchise or manufacturing operation, not a venture-scale technology company. Structure financing accordingly: debt, revenue-based financing, or strategic partnerships with retailers who can absorb CapEx.","Energy costs are the silent killer of hardware businesses. Plenty's facilities consumed megawatts of power 24/7. At $0.15-0.25 per kWh in California, energy alone cost $2-4 per pound of produce. Modern founders building energy-intensive businesses must co-locate with cheap power: data centers near hydroelectric dams, manufacturing in regions with solar surplus, or vertical farms in Iceland with geothermal energy. Alternatively, vertically integrate energy production: rooftop solar, on-site batteries, or power purchase agreements. Use tools like Aurora Solar for modeling and Stem for battery optimization. Never assume energy costs will decrease—plan for increases.","Pivoting between crops or markets without fixing core economics is rearranging deck chairs on the Titanic. Plenty pivoted from leafy greens to strawberries to international expansion, searching for a wedge where unit economics worked. This is a red flag that the fundamental business model is broken. Modern founders should identify the single biggest constraint (for Plenty: energy cost per photon delivered) and obsess over solving it before expanding. Use constraint-based thinking: What is the one variable that, if improved 10x, makes the entire business viable? Focus all R&D there. For vertical farming, that might be genetically engineering crops that grow with 90% less light, or developing quantum dot LEDs with 5x efficiency.","Mission-driven businesses still need to make money. Plenty's sustainability narrative attracted top-tier investors and talent, but good intentions don't pay electricity bills. Modern founders should separate the mission (why the world needs this) from the business model (how we capture value). Use Jobs-to-be-Done framework: customers hire products to solve problems, not to save the planet. Plenty's customers hired lettuce to make salads—they didn't care about water savings if it cost 2x more. Find the wedge where your sustainable solution is also the cheapest, fastest, or highest quality option. Tesla succeeded because their cars were desirable first, sustainable second.","Beware of investors who push growth over profitability. SoftBank's $200M investment likely came with aggressive growth targets and pressure to deploy capital quickly. This forced Plenty to build expensive flagship facilities before optimizing the model. Modern founders should seek investors aligned with capital-efficient growth. Use metrics like CAC payback period, LTV/CAC ratio, and months to profitability. If an investor pushes you to raise a mega-round before proving unit economics, run. Better to bootstrap or raise smaller amounts from angels who understand the long game. Tools like Carta for cap table management and Pulley for scenario modeling help maintain control.","Technology should reduce costs, not just improve quality. Plenty's AI-driven climate control and robotics improved yield consistency and reduced labor, but didn't fundamentally change the cost structure. Modern founders should ask: Does this technology make the product 10x cheaper, or just 10% better? Focus on cost-reduction innovations first, quality improvements second. For vertical farming, that might mean developing ultra-low-cost LED panels using perovskite materials, or breeding crops that thrive in ambient light conditions. Use Design for Manufacturing principles and tools like Fusion 360 for cost optimization from day one."],
