    id: "2069",
    name: "Mobike",
    description: "Unlock any bike anywhere with your phone, ride it, dump it wherever—turning entire cities into your personal bike rack.",
    industry: "Industrials",
    cause_of_death: "Burned $900M flooding cities with bikes that earned 30¢ per ride but cost $300 each, while users dumped them in rivers.",
    death_category: "unit_economics",
    money_raised: 900000000,
    money_burned: 900000000,
    founded_year: 2015,
    died_year: 2018,
    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Hardware-as-a-Service requires 10x better unit economics than you think. Mobike needed bikes to generate $1+ per day to be viable, but achieved $0.30. In asset-heavy models, your financial model must account for worst-case depreciation, theft, and vandalism from day one. If the math doesn't work at 50% utilization with 30% annual loss rates, don't build it. The margin for error in physical goods businesses is razor-thin compared to software.","Dockless is a feature, not a business model. The 'leave it anywhere' convenience that delighted users created catastrophic operational costs. Every efficiency gain for the user became a cost center for the company. The lesson: user convenience must be balanced against operational feasibility. Sometimes friction (docking stations) is the price of sustainability. Uber succeeded partly because drivers absorbed vehicle costs; Mobike owned all the downside of asset ownership with none of the upside of asset appreciation.","Subsidized demand is not product-market fit. Mobike and Ofo both mistook subsidy-driven growth for genuine demand. When rides cost $0.15 (subsidized from $0.50), millions used the service. When subsidies ended, usage dropped 60-80%. The real test of PMF in marketplace or logistics businesses is: will customers pay full freight, and will the business be profitable at that price? Growth at any cost obscures this truth until it's too late.","In two-sided marketplaces with commoditized supply, winner-take-all is a myth. Bikes are interchangeable. Users don't care about brand; they care about proximity. This means no network effects, no lock-in, and no pricing power. The only moat is density, which requires continuous capital infusion. If your competitive advantage is 'we have more stuff in more places,' you're in a capital efficiency race you'll likely lose. Contrast with Uber: drivers and riders both benefit from network density, creating compounding advantages. Mobike had linear advantages at best.","Municipal relationships are not partnerships; they're regulatory capture risks. Cities initially welcomed bike-sharing, then turned hostile when sidewalks became cluttered and rivers filled with bikes. Mobike treated cities as customers but had no formal agreements, no revenue sharing, and no accountability mechanisms. When political winds shifted, they had no leverage. Any business operating in public space must formalize relationships with revenue-sharing or service contracts, or risk being regulated out of existence overnight."],
    market_potential_score: 5,
    rebuild_difficulty: 2,
    tags: ["iot"],
