    id: "2551",
    name: "DaDaABC",
    description: "Online platform connecting Chinese kids with native English tutors via 1-on-1 video lessons, backed by $863M from Tiger Global.",
    industry: "Consumer",
    cause_of_death: "Regulatory crackdown on for-profit tutoring in 2021 made the entire business model illegal overnight in China.",
    death_category: "regulatory",
    money_raised: 863000000,
    money_burned: 863000000,
    founded_year: 2013,
    died_year: 2021,
    country: "China",
    founder_count: 1,
    employee_count: 0,
    lessons_learned: ["Regulatory risk is not a probability distribution—it is a binary outcome in authoritarian markets. Diversify geography or accept that your entire investment can be legislated to zero overnight. DaDa's investors learned that Chinese government priorities (social stability, ideology) trump economic efficiency. Any business dependent on government tolerance in China, Russia, or similar regimes must model 100% loss scenarios.","Prepaid revenue models create catastrophic liability in rapid shutdowns. DaDa collected tuition 6-12 months in advance, which looked like negative working capital and strong unit economics. In reality, it was an unfunded liability that became a bankruptcy accelerant when refunds were demanded simultaneously. Modern SaaS companies should avoid long prepayment cycles unless funds are escrowed or revenue is truly earned (usage-based).","Marketplace liquidity is fragile when supply is commoditized. DaDa's teachers were interchangeable English speakers, not unique experts. When the platform shut down, teachers instantly moved to competitors or direct-to-consumer models (Cambly, Preply, private WeChat groups). There was no moat. True marketplace power requires either unique supply (Uber's driver density in a city) or unique demand aggregation (Amazon's customer base). DaDa had neither.","Unit economics must work at maturity, not just at scale. DaDa's 30-40% gross margins and $500-1000 CAC meant the business was fundamentally unprofitable without continuous fundraising. The plan was to reach scale, reduce CAC through brand, and expand into adjacent products. This is the classic venture-subsidized growth trap. If margins don't improve dramatically with scale (software leverage, network effects), you are building a services business with tech aesthetics. Modern founders should model profitability at 10,000 customers, not 10 million.","AI tutors are now viable for structured learning, fundamentally changing EdTech economics. In 2013, DaDa needed human teachers because speech recognition, natural language understanding, and adaptive curriculum were unsolved. Today, GPT-4 with voice mode, ElevenLabs for natural speech, and fine-tuned models for language correction can deliver 70-80% of the value at 1% of the cost. The remaining 20-30% (cultural context, motivation, human connection) still requires humans, but a hybrid model (AI for drills and grammar, humans for conversation practice) could achieve $50/month price points with 80% gross margins. DaDa's failure cleared the path for AI-native language learning.","Fixed teacher-student pairing was a differentiation trap. DaDa's core feature—students keeping the same teacher long-term—created operational rigidity (teacher churn, scheduling conflicts, supply-demand mismatches) and prevented the marketplace from optimizing. It was a feature parents liked but that destroyed operational efficiency. Modern platforms should test whether customers actually value consistency or whether it is a perceived need that can be designed away (Uber does not let you keep the same driver). Sometimes the differentiation that wins early customers is the constraint that kills you at scale.","Foreign capital in sensitive sectors is a political liability. DaDa's cap table (Tiger Global, Warburg Pincus) made it a visible target during China's tech crackdown. The government framed the tutoring ban partly as reducing foreign influence on Chinese children's education. Domestic competitors with state-connected investors (like Yuanfudao, backed by Tencent) received softer treatment or pivoted more successfully. Founders in regulated industries should consider whether foreign VC money creates more risk than value, especially in markets with nationalist policy trends."],
